Headlines.SeoHeadline: KNOC in on El Paso E&P Purchase
Headlines.Headline: KNOC in on El Paso E&P Purchase

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Ryan Dezember and Min-Jeong LeeThe Korea National Oil Corporation is a part of the group that has  agreed to pay $7.15 billion for El Paso Corp.'s   exploration-and-production business, according to people familiar with  the matter.Known as KNOC, the government-backed company's involvement in the  buyout was not disclosed when the deal was announced last month by a  group of investors led by Apollo Global Management LLC.At the time, Riverstone Holdings LLC., an energy focused  private-equity firm, and Len Blavatnik's Access Industries were named as  partners. It is unclear what stake each partner will have in EP Energy,  as the business is now called.A spokeswoman for Apollo declined to comment, as did a spokesman for  Riverstone. A representative for KNOC could not immediately be reached. A  spokesman for Access Industries didn't immediately respond to a request  for comment.KNOC's participation comes as national oil companies, particularly  those in Asia, are increasingly staking claim to North America's oil and  gas renaissance.In November KNOC teamed up with the trading and construction unit of  Samsung Group to buy Parallel Petroleum from Apollo for $771.5 million.  Parallel operates oil and gas fields in Texas and New Mexico.In addition to those assets, KNOC has stakes in shallow-water fields  off Louisiana and Alabama as well as a one-third interest in a south  Texas shale field operated by Anadarko Petroleum Corp.EP Energy's assets are spread throughout the U.S. and include fields in Egypt and the deep waters off Brazil.El Paso planned last year to spin off EP Energy as a separate public  company. But in November, before it separated the unit from its pipeline  business, Houston-based El Paso agreed to be acquired by Kinder Morgan  Inc.  for $21.1 billion.Kinder Morgan said at the onset that it would sell the exploration  and production business, aiming to close the deal this spring, around  the time the larger merger is finalized.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: CFO Optimism on the Rise
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: CFO Optimism on the Rise

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Upswing in optimism. New surveys just out show that CFOs are increasingly upbeat and ready to hire.
The latest quarterly Duke/CFO Magazine Survey (PDF) checked in with 873 global CFOs. They plan to expand their work forces by 2.1% on average over the next 12 months -- a pace that would bring the unemployment rate down below 8% if all companies did the same. More than two-thirds say their companies are trying to fill vacant positions -- and they're recruiting more aggressively to fill the slots. They also plan to boost capital spending by more than 7% -- the energy and manufacturing sectors will see the biggest outlays.
"Increases in CFO optimism have historically preceded improvements in the overall economy," said Duke professor John Graham, director of the survey. The U.S. CFO Optimism Index, meanwhile, rose to 59 from 53 sequentially, back up to the long-term average.
The AICPA's quarterly CPA Outlook Index – out this morning – shows more muted optimism. About 14% of the 1,358 CFOs and controllers surveyed plan to hire this quarter – up from 10% in Q4. A further 20% said they need people, but they're hesitant to hire. They also expect profit and revenue increases this quarter – reversing two quarters of gloominess and they see R&D spending improving slightly.
Meanwhile, Tatum's Index of Business Conditions (PDF) posted the largest one-month gain in a year in February. Tatum's Sam Norwood told CFOworld that "the trend toward recovery that began in September has resumed as of March 1 after a one-month rest."
Question: Are Ledger readers feeling the optimism, too – enough to hire and boost spending? Let us know.
THE DAY AHEAD:
Weekly jobless claims are expected to edge up slightly to 353,000 – but these have been coming in ahead of forecasts lately.
Greece is inching toward completion of its debt restructuring ahead of today's deadline (more below). The ECB is expected to hold rates steady at its policy meeting. ECB President Mario Draghi will face questions on the central bank's funding operations at a news conference later.
And House Republicans are meeting behind closed doors to smooth over differences on spending limits in Budget Committee Chairman Paul Ryan's budget.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: New Chapter for Kodak
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: New Chapter for Kodak

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Top of the news: Kodak filed for Chapter 11 overnight – it was just a matter of time as it ran low on cash. But it secured $950 million in financing from Citigroup, so it will keep operating through bankruptcy proceedings. The company listed $5.1 billion in assets and $6.75 billion in debts in its documents filed in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Manhattan. Read the filing here (PDF). It also named Dominic Di Napoli, a vice chairman at FTI Consulting, as its chief restructuring officer to help steer the company through bankruptcy court, the WSJ reports. The plan is to exit Chapter 11 next year after cutting costs and selling off some patents.
Kodak CFO Ann McCorvey said in a court filing that the company plans to sell significant assets. Read McCorvey's filing here (PDF). This is a huge test for McCorvey – she's only been Kodak's CFO for about two years. CFOJ's Max Murphy profiled McCorvey in our CFOs to Watch in 2012 series, noting that the crisis could bolster her reputation if she's able to steer Kodak through this storm.
The day ahead: Huge day for tech. Microsoft, Intel and Google all report after markets close. Google has been on a hiring spree lately as it ramps up its offensive against Apple in mobile and Facebook in social networking. That will likely make an impact on operating profit, but revenue is expected to come in strong. Microsoft and Intel are both expected to report lackluster results. But we'll be looking for a better sense of their strategies to revive PC sales and deepen their footprints in the mobile sector.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: The Morning Ledger: New Chapter for Kodak

Headlines.Author: John Kell
Headlines.Headline: Moody's Lifts Kinder Morgan Energy Outlook; Sees Improved Leverage

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Moody's Investors Service lifted its outlook on Kinder Morgan Energy Partners LP KMP to stable from negative, saying the pipeline operator's leverage has peaked and should improve over the next year. "With the bulge of large capital projects behind the company and its forward cash flows reflecting the impact of those recently completed projects and acquisitions, Kinder Morgan's leverage should remain in line with its rating," said Ken Austin, Moody's vice president. Kinder Morgan, which last year said it plans to spend $1.4 billion in expansions and acquisitions this year, already detailed plans to invest an additional $100 million to expand the scope of its venture in the Eagle Ford shale formation in Texas with Copano Energy LLC CPNO.

Headlines.Author: Lynn Cowan
Headlines.Headline: HCA Aiming To Sell 160M Shares At $27 To $30/Shr In IPO

PARAGRAPH.#text: Hospital operator HCA Holdings Inc. is hoping to sell 160 million shares at $27 to $30 apiece in its IPO early next month, according to people familiar with its plans. The company, which will be the third private equity-backed initial public offering to raise more than $1 billion so far this year, is scheduled to launch its road show starting Tuesday and price its IPO on March 9. The stock would begin trading the next day on the New York Stock Exchange under the symbol HCA. Although the company hasn't yet filed an updated prospectus with the Security and Exchange Commission, it is expected to do so early next week.

Headlines.Author: Lynn Cowan
Headlines.Headline: Kinder Morgan IPO Prices At $30 Per Share; Above Range

PARAGRAPH.#text: Energy company Kinder Morgan Inc. priced its initial public offering at $30 a share Thursday night, at a price above its expected $26 to $29 price range. It sold 95.5 million shares of stock in the deal, making it the largest private-equity backed IPO ever seen in the U.S. Kinder Morgan on Thursday said the size of the offering was increased above the previously announced plan of 80 million shares, based on strong demand. The company's offering was widely expected to draw strong investor interest, with its marketing road shows packed with attendees in the past week, according to Scott Sweet, managing director of IPOBoutique.com.
